# Twelve-Factor methodology

When adding features, wiring services, or changing deployment behavior, align with the [Twelve-Factor App](https://12factor.net/) methodology. Use the factor names as a checklist; details live on the site.

## I. Codebase

One tracked codebase, many deploys. Do not fork “secret” variants of the app per environment—use config (factor III) and the same repo for all deploys.

## II. Dependencies

Declare dependencies explicitly (`package.json`, lockfile, Docker images, `compose.yml` services). Do not rely on undeclared global tools on the host.

## III. Config

**Store config in the environment** (e.g. `process.env`, `import.meta.env` only for non-secrets). Never commit secrets; document keys in [`.env.example`](.env.example). No environment-specific constants baked into source when an env var exists (e.g. `SCRIBE_URL`, `FLIGHT_PORT`, `GEMINI_API_KEY`).

## IV. Backing services

Treat databases, caches, Scribe, Redis, etc. as **attached resources** addressable by URL/config. Swapping a dev Redis for a managed one should be a config change, not a code fork.

## V. Build, release, run

Separate **build** (install, compile assets) from **run** (process serving traffic). Avoid writing build-time artifacts that the running app mutates as source of truth; runtime state belongs in backing services or explicit stores.

## VI. Processes

App processes should be **stateless** and share-nothing where possible. Session or durable state goes to Redis/DB/Scribe—not local disk on the web tier (except ephemeral temp).

## VII. Port binding

Export HTTP (and similar) by **binding a port**; read port from config. Do not assume fixed hosts baked into code for server-side listeners.

## VIII. Concurrency

Scale by running **more processes** (or replicas), not by bolting concurrency into a single giant in-memory singleton for app-wide mutable state.

## IX. Disposability

**Fast startup** and **graceful shutdown** (handle signals, drain in-flight work, close connections). Avoid long mandatory init that blocks health checks.

## X. Dev/prod parity

Keep dev, staging, and prod **similar**: same dependency declarations, same env-driven config shape, same backing-service contracts. Prefer `compose.yml` / documented local flows over “works only on my laptop” shortcuts.

## XI. Logs

Treat logs as **streams to stdout/stderr**; let the platform aggregate. Do not require a local log file path for core operation in production paths.

## XII. Admin processes

Run migrations, one-off scripts, and admin tasks as **one-off processes** with the same release and config as the app—not as special long-lived branches of the web server.

## Repo-specific reminders

- **Flight / Koa / Vite:** ports and origins come from env (see [`.env.example`](.env.example)); proxy and `VITE_*` must stay consistent with where Koa actually listens.
- **Kota0 / Scribe:** `SCRIBE_URL` and related limits are config, not hardcoded production hosts in app code.

When a change would violate a factor, call it out and propose a compliant alternative.
